thought.text:
## Phase 3: Root Cause Analysis

I've identified the root cause. In `AddAutoSpinTimeout()`:

```csharp
private void AddAutoSpinTimeout ()
{
    // Only add timeout if we are initialized and not already spinning
    if (App is { } && (_timeout is { } || !App.Initialized))
    {
        return;
    }

    _timeout = App?.AddTimeout (...);
}
```

The condition returns early if `App` exists but is not initialized. When `AutoSpin = true` is set before the view is added to the visual tree (which is the typical pattern), `App` is often null at that point, so `App?.AddTimeout(...)` does nothing. And there's no mechanism to retry adding the timeout later when the view gets added to the tree.

The fix: Override `OnSuperViewChanged` to add the auto-spin timeout when the view gets added to a parent that has access to an initialized App. We also need a flag to track the "intended" AutoSpin state.

Let me now look at the base class `OnSuperViewChanged` to understand how to properly override it.

